cluding drag queens, cosmetic enhancements, trans fertility, and gender-non-conforming childhoods. Male Femininities illuminates what happens when we decouple femininity from female bodies and how even the smallest cracks and fissures in the normative order can disrupt, challenge, and in some cases reaffirm our existing sex-gender regime. This volume pluralizes the concept of male femininities and leads readers through an exploration of how gender, sex, and sexuality are manifested in the United States today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEffeminacy. 0aFemininity. 0aMasculinity. 0aMenxIdentity. 0aSex role. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aHalberstam.  abody technology.  aeffeminacy.  afemininity.  agender binary.  agender inequality.  agender revolution.  agender.  ahealth.  ahegemonic masculinity.  aheteronormativity.  ahomosexuality.  amale femininity.  amale pregnancy.  aqueer theory.  aqueer.  asexualities.  asocial constructionism.1 aAdair, Joshua G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, Rusty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaver, Travis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkowitz, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkowitz, Dana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBishop, Katelynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonvissuto, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouncilor, Kc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDansky, Steven F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrensaft, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/